<subSubSection lastPageId="41" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="40.[151,1436,1842,2011]" lastBlockId="41.[151,1437,151,1220]" lastPageId="41" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,466,1914,1939]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Differential Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Among members of the 
<emphasis box="[743,845,1915,1939]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Foliobba</emphasis>
group, most similar in dorsal habitus to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2011" box="[1298,1436,1915,1939]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="infoveola">
<emphasis box="[1298,1318,1915,1938]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1332,1436,1915,1939]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">infoveola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[159,252,1950,1974]" captionStart="FIGURE 51" captionStartId="183.[151,250,1753,1776]" captionTargetBox="[199,1395,209,1718]" captionTargetId="figure-27@183.[183,1404,193,1732]" captionTargetPageId="183" captionText="FIGURE 51. Hydraena striolata, holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, venter, and abdominal apex." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5283494" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5283494/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Figs. 51</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[263,295,1950,1974]" captionStart="FIGURE 54" captionStartId="185.[151,250,1753,1776]" captionTargetBox="[216,1372,209,1718]" captionTargetId="figure-25@185.[198,1388,193,1732]" captionTargetPageId="185" captionText="FIGURE 54. Hydraena infoveola, holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and venter." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5283500" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5283500/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">54</figureCitation>
); differing therefrom by the smaller size (ca. 1.43 vs. 
<quantity box="[892,996,1950,1974]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.58" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" unit="mm" value="1.58">1.58 mm</quantity>
), the brown color bands on each side of the pronotal fascia (testaceous in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2011" box="[523,660,1987,2011]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="infoveola">
<emphasis box="[523,543,1987,2010]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[556,660,1987,2011]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">infoveola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the slightly more impressed pronotal foveae PF2, and the more narrowly separated metaventral plaques. Males of the two species are additionally differentiated by differences in the shapes of the tibiae, and by the striolate area on the fifth abdominal ventrite of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2011" box="[1025,1154,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="striolata">
<emphasis box="[1025,1045,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1059,1154,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">striolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1168,1251,188,212]" captionStart="FIGURE 51" captionStartId="183.[151,250,1753,1776]" captionTargetBox="[199,1395,209,1718]" captionTargetId="figure-27@183.[183,1404,193,1732]" captionTargetPageId="183" captionText="FIGURE 51. Hydraena striolata, holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, venter, and abdominal apex." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5283494" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5283494/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 51</figureCitation>
). The aedeagi of the two species distinctively differ (
<figureCitation box="[551,644,223,247]" captionStart="FIGURES 52–53" captionStartId="184.[151,264,1613,1636]" captionTargetBox="[256,1343,211,1564]" captionTargetId="figure-32@184.[226,1360,193,1592]" captionTargetPageId="184" captionText="FIGURES 52–53. Aedeagi of holotypes. 52. H. foliobba. 53. H. striolata." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5283496" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5283496/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Figs. 53</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[657,689,223,247]" captionStart="FIGURES 56–57" captionStartId="187.[151,264,1650,1673]" captionTargetBox="[282,1301,215,1623]" captionTargetId="figure-29@187.[263,1323,193,1629]" captionTargetPageId="187" captionText="FIGURES 56–57. Aedeagi of holotypes. 56. H. infoveola. 57. H. otiarca." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5283506" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5283506/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">56</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1437,151,1220]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,344,259,284]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" reason="1">Description.</emphasis>
Size: 
<typeStatus box="[428,526,260,284]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">holotype</typeStatus>
(length/width, mm): body (length to elytral apices) 1.43/0.58; head 0.25/0.34; pronotum 0.34/0.42, PA 0.36, PB 0.36; elytra 0.84/0.58. Dorsum of head piceous; pronotum light brown in front of and very narrowly behind piceous fascia, ratios of color bands, as measured in midline, ca. 6/14/3; elytra dark brown; legs and maxillary palpi brown to dark brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1437,151,1220]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Frons punctures slightly larger than 1xef; interstices shining, 1–3xpd. Clypeus microreticulate laterally, very finely sparsely punctate medially. Mentum and postmentum very sparsely very finely punctulate, shining. Genae raised, shining, without posterior ridge. Pronotum cordiform, median 2/3 of anterior margin emarginate; punctures on disc ca. 1xpd those of frons, interstices shining, 1–3xpd, punctures slightly larger and denser at anterior and posterior; PF1 absent or obsolete; PF2 very shallow, obsolete; PF3 moderately deep; PF4 absent.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1437,151,1220]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Elytra with summit of posterior declivity at or very near midlength; lateral explanate moderately wide; on basal 1/3 punctures ca. 1xpd largest pronotal punctures, punctures becoming gradually smaller toward posterior. Intervals not raised, shining, on disc ca. 1–2xpd, as are interstices between punctures of a row. Apices in dorsal aspect weakly separately rounded, in posterior aspect margins forming shallow angle with one another.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1437,151,1220]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
Ratios of P2 width and plaque shape (P2/w/l/s) ca. 4/2/7/3. P1 laminate; median carina sinuate in profile. P2 raised, l/w ca. 2/1, sides slightly converging toward apex. Plaques moderately wide, converging very slightly anteriorly, weakly raised, located at sides of deep, median depression. Metaventrite with short low ridge extended from each mesoventral coxal cavity. AIS width at straight posterior margin ca. 1.5x P2. All legs long and very slender. Profemur (male) with small, sharply pointed tubercle next to trochanter; protibia slightly arcuate, gradually increasing in width from base to apex. Mesotibia moderately arcuate, ca. to same degree as protibia. Metatibia straight. Fifth ventrite median area (male) striolate (with very fine, closely spaced, parallel impressed lines) (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 51" captionStartId="183.[151,250,1753,1776]" captionTargetBox="[199,1395,209,1718]" captionTargetId="figure-27@183.[183,1404,193,1732]" captionTargetPageId="183" captionText="FIGURE 51. Hydraena striolata, holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, venter, and abdominal apex." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5283494" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5283494/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 51</figureCitation>
). Abdominal apex symmetrical; last tergite (male) deeply notched. Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[1081,1164,980,1004]" captionStart="FIGURES 52–53" captionStartId="184.[151,264,1613,1636]" captionTargetBox="[256,1343,211,1564]" captionTargetId="figure-32@184.[226,1360,193,1592]" captionTargetPageId="184" captionText="FIGURES 52–53. Aedeagi of holotypes. 52. H. foliobba. 53. H. striolata." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5283496" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5283496/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 53</figureCitation>
) main piece with large, sharply pointed, markedly arcuate process on left side; distal piece large in both ventral and lateral views.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1200,1052,1076]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1437,151,1220]" box="[199,1200,1052,1076]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,333,1052,1076]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named in reference to the striolate area on the male fifth abdominal ventrite.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1437,151,1220]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1087,1112]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" reason="1">Distribution.</emphasis>
Currently known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[732,780,1088,1112]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">type</typeStatus>
locality, Tanbugal Afore village, in central Area 8, at or very near the border with Area 7; elevation 
<quantity box="[640,767,1124,1148]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" unit="m" value="400.0" valueMax="500.0" valueMin="300.0">300–500 m</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[782,882,1124,1148]" captionStart="FIGURES 511–514" captionStartId="403.[151,263,1650,1673]" captionTargetBox="[165,1421,197,1591]" captionTargetId="figure-20@403.[165,1421,193,1629]" captionTargetPageId="403" captionText="FIGURES 511–514. Geographical distributions of Hydraena species." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5284125" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5284125/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 514</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1437,151,1220]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,273,1160,1184]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" reason="1">Notes.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus box="[337,435,1160,1184]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">holotype</typeStatus>
has a very narrow groove across part of the occipital area of the head (
<figureCitation box="[1284,1371,1160,1184]" captionStart="FIGURE 51" captionStartId="183.[151,250,1753,1776]" captionTargetBox="[199,1395,209,1718]" captionTargetId="figure-27@183.[183,1404,193,1732]" captionTargetPageId="183" captionText="FIGURE 51. Hydraena striolata, holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, venter, and abdominal apex." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5283494" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5283494/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 51</figureCitation>
); this groove, apparently an anomaly, is not present on the 
<typeStatus box="[742,1039,1196,1220]" isOtherTypeStatus="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">other specimens examined</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
